Historic Place - Engine House Fire Engine House is historically significant as an example of an early, purpose-built fire station. The building is an important marker in the development of Nelson's fire fighting services and is the only remaining physical link with Nelson's Provincial Council Buildings. The Provincial Council Buildings were an important part of Nelson's history and the use of similar materials and the same architectural detail in Fire Engine House gives the structure aesthetic and architectural importance. The site has social value as it is intimately connected in the community mind with the notorious Maungatapu murders that caused a sensation in the district.

A significant portion of Bankwood Park is actually part of 126 Comries Road.  The land is owned by 126 Comries Road but appears visually to be part of Bankwood Park. Central to Tawa Dental Care's philosophy is the belief in the transformative power of a healthy, glowing smile. The clinic's array of services includes fillings, root canal treatments, extractions, and wisdom teeth administration, dealing with common dental problems with precision and empathy. For those seeking restoration or improvement, Tawa Dental Care uses implants, crowns, bridges, dentures, dental braces, Invisalign, veneers, teeth whitening, and extensive smile makeovers. Each treatment is tailored to fulfill the individual's demands and expectations, using the most up to date dental modern technology and techniques to make sure the best outcomes.  The group at Tawa Dental Care is a cumulative of very skilled experts, passionate concerning dental health and dedicated to continuous education and training. This makes sure that every procedure, from regular examinations to complicated surgeries, is performed with the utmost knowledge and care. The clinic's financial investment in state-of-the-art technology, including electronic radiography, dental lasers, and microscopes, highlights its dedication to accuracy, comfort, and minimally invasive treatment.  Located at 196 Main Road Tawa, the clinic is comfortably situated in the Tawa shopping centre, offering enough complimentary auto parking and simple access for all patients.

opening_comment: Should  SH29 be a trunk highway?
closing_comment: Yes - NZTA national strategic route and it links the 'Golden triangle' cities of Auckland, Hamilton and Tauranga. The fact state highways have single- or double-digit numbers is no longer relevant.

opening_comment: Should SH57 be a trunk highway?
closing_comment: SH 57 is classified as a national strategic route by NZTA, since it links Wellington (port, 400k), Palmerston North (80k) and Napier-Hastings (port, 130k). The fact it is has a two digit number is not important any more.

opening_comment: Should SH33 be a trunk highway?
closing_comment: Yes - NZTA national and regional strategic state highways are generally classified as trunk. SH 33 is a regional strategic road (links Tauranga with Rotorua and ultimately Wellington)

closing_comment: North of Kawakawa, SH 1 is non-strategic hence is classified primary.

opening_comment: Should SH 29 not be primary as SH24,27,28 are all primary.  Would seem to make more sense
closing_comment: SH 29 is the main road linking Hamilton and Tauranga, NZ's 4th and 5th largest cities, and NZTA classifies it as a nationally strategic highway. Whether a highway has a one or two digit number is no longer relevant.

opening_comment: Should SH 57 not be primary as SH 54,56 are all primary. Would seem to make more sense
closing_comment: SH 57 is classified by the NZTA as a strategic route, hence is classified as a trunk. SH 56 and SH 54 are non-strategic so are primary.

opening_comment: Hi, we were using the Android app, osmand, navigating around New Zealand two weeks ago, and ran in to one error (honestly, we were quite impressed with the quality of the maps and navigation). We continued on SH6, and navigation resumed as normal.  I'm not sure if this is a problem with the map database or the Android application - but thought that I would log/note the error.  Best regards,  Dave
closing_comment: Hi Constable.  Thanks for looking in to this.  I originally thought that there might be a conflict in the openstreetmap database - clearly not. I then have to assume that there is a problem (bug?) with the navigation facility of OSMAND.  Best regards,  Dave
